WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
You can add Dark Mode to your Shiny for R apps in just a few easy steps.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:10.000
Here I have a simple app with a plaque that reacts to a slider input that's in the sidebar of a page sidebar.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:17.000
In order for this to work, you're going to need to use both Shiny and BSLib together, and make sure that you're using one of BSLib's page functions.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:21.000
Then, inside the sidebar, I'm simply going to add InputDarkMode.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:26.000
Now, when users open your app, InputDarkMode will choose the color scheme that matches their system profile.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:30.000
It also gives them a toggle button where they can switch between light and dark mode.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:33.000
For most apps, this is all you need. You can stop right here.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:37.000
But in our app, we have a plot, and we would like the plot to match the current color mode.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:41.000
To do that, I'm going to use the thematic package, and simply call thematic on.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:46.000
Thematic will automatically update my ggplot and other types of plots to match the current color mode.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:52.000
For more complicated tasks, I can give InputDarkMode an ID so that I can react to the current color mode on the server.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:56.000
I hope you enjoyed this tip. Go make some beautiful Shiny apps that you can use at night.

